source.Name: Total population
source.Summary: Population: Total population and distribution by age and sex estimated to be consistent with the population by age and sex of the (a) 1979, 1989, 1999, 2009, 2019 censuses; (b) adjusted for under/over count; (c) adjusted for under enumeration of children under age 15; (d) official estimates through 2022; and with estimates of the subsequent trends in fertility, mortality and international migration.

source.Name: Total fertility rate
source.Summary: Fertility: Total fertility rate and age pattern of fertility based on: (a) official estimates of age-specific fertility rates through 2018; (b) registered births classified by age of mother and the underlying female population by age through 2007; (c) birth-histories data from the 1988, 1997, 2002 DHS and 1994 IDS and 2013-2014, 2020-2021 MICS; (d) births in the household in the preceding 12 (or 24) months classified by age of mother from the 1989, 1999, 2009, 2019 censuses and 1994 IDS and 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2015, 2016, 2017-2018, 2018-2019, 2019, 2020 Annual APC and 2006, 2010-2011 MICS and 2014 IPHS; (e) indirect estimates based on the increment of cohort parities between successive censuses or surveys such as the 1945-2018 Estimates; (f) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 1979, 1989, 1999, 2009, 2019 censuses and 2000, 2006, 2010-2011 MICS and 2005 AIS and 2007 Annual APC; (g) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the own-children method of fertility estimation to the 1989, 1999, 2009 censuses and 2003 WHS and 2006, 2010-2011 MICS; (h) cohort-completed fertility backdated by the mean age of childbearing from the 1988, 1997, 2002 DHS and 1989, 1999, 2009, 2019 censuses and 1994 IDS and 2000, 2006, 2010-2011, 2013-2014, 2020-2021 MICS and 2005 AIS and 2005, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2011 Annual APC. In addition, the indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 2020-2021 MICS have been considered.

source.Name: Life expectancy at birth
source.Summary: Overall Mortality: Life expectancy at birth and age pattern of mortality based on: estimates using CD North model life tables and estimates of infant and under-five mortality (5q0), and adult mortality (45q15). In addition, the (a) registered deaths by age and sex available through 2021; (b) adjusted for underregistration; (c) adjusted for underreporting of infant and child deaths; (d) mortality rates for older ages were adjusted have been considered.

source.Name: Age Mortality
source.Summary: Adult and Old Age Mortality: Estimates derived from: (a) recent household deaths data by age and sex from the 1989 Census and 2001-2002 NHS and 2009 NSMSP and 2011, 2012, 2013, 2015, 2016, 2017-2018, 2018-2019 Annual APC and 2014 IPHS; (b) recent household deaths adjusted at adult ages for underregistration using death distribution methods; (c) siblings deaths from the 1991 VLHS and 1995-1998 VLS and 2009 NSMSP; (d) maternal orphanhood from the 1995-1998 VLS and 2000, 2006, 2010-2011, 2013-2014 MICS and 2005 AIS and 2009 NSMSP; (e) paternal orphanhood from the 1995-1998 VLS and 2000, 2006, 2010-2011, 2013-2014 MICS and 2005 AIS and 2009 NSMSP; (f) indirect estimates of male adult mortality based on female widowhood data from the 1988, 1997, 2002 DHS and 1989, 1999, 2009 censuses and 2000, 2006, 2010-2011, 2013-2014 MICS and 2005 AIS and 2007, 2011, 2015 Annual APC; (g) intercensal survivorship from successive census age distributions; (h) estimates of under-five, adult and old age mortality. In addition, the (a) deaths by age and sex available from Register through 2021; (b) adjusted for underregistration; (c) recent household deaths data by age and sex from the 1999 Census and 2007, 2008 Annual APC; (d) recent household deaths adjusted at adult ages for underregistration using the growth balance method; (e) recent household deaths adjusted at adult ages for underregistration using death distribution methods; (f) maternal orphanhood from the 1991 VLHS and 2020-2021 MICS; (g) paternal orphanhood from the 1991 VLHS and 2020-2021 MICS; (h) indirect estimates of female adult mortality based on male widowhood data from the 1989, 1999, 2009 censuses and 1997, 2002 DHS and 2000 MICS and 2005 AIS and 2007, 2011, 2015 Annual APC; (i) intercensal survivorship from successive census age distributions have been considered.

source.Name: Infant/child mortality
source.Summary: Child Mortality: Under-five mortality based on: (a) direct estimates from births and deaths under-five calculated from full birth histories data from the 1988, 1997, 2002 DHS and 1994 IDS and 1995-1998 VLS and 2013-2014 MICS; (b) indirect estimates from data on children ever born and surviving from the 1989 Census and 2000 MICS; (c) recent household deaths from the 2011, 2012, 2013, 2015, 2016, 2017-2018, 2018-2019, 2020, 2021 Annual APC and 2014 IPHS and 2015 Migration Survey and 2019 Census; (d) International estimates used up to 2021. In addition, the (a) direct estimates from births and deaths under-five calculated from full birth histories data from the 2020-2021 MICS; (b) indirect estimates from data on children ever born and surviving from the 1999, 2009, 2019 censuses; (c) recent household deaths from the 1999, 2009 censuses and 2003 SAVY and 2004 Migration Survey and 2005, 2007, 2008 Annual APC and 2006 Family Survey have been considered.

source.Name: International migration
source.Summary: Migration: International migration based on: (a) official figures of net international migration flows, and assumed subsequent trends in international migration; (b) information on foreign-born populations from censuses and registers from major countries of destination; (c) estimates derived as the differences between overall population growth and natural increase; (d) UNHCR statistics on the number of refugees in the main countries of asylum.
